  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This research dataset, deposited on the NCCR MARVEL Materials Cloud platform in 2024, supports the implementation of density functional Bogoliubov-de Gennes theory for superconductors within the SIESTA code. Produced by a Dutch-Spanish collaboration spanning Utrecht University and the Institut Catal\u00e0 de Nanoci\u00e8ncia i Nanotecnologia, it has already been formally cited by its companion journal article in <em>Physical Review B</em> and sits within a reuse network of eight downstream scholarly connections, signalling that it is functioning as intended within its specialist community.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The dataset serves as the computational backbone for a methodological advance in condensed matter physics: the integration of Bogoliubov-de Gennes formalism with density functional theory inside SIESTA, a widely used electronic-structure code based on localised basis sets. By making the underlying input files, parameters, and reproducible workflows openly available through Materials Cloud, Reho, Wittemeier, Kole, Ordej\u00f3n, and Zanolli have provided the community with the means to verify, extend, and build upon their theoretical framework. The explicit linking of the dataset to the published <em>Physical Review B</em> article (DOI 10.1103/PhysRevB.110.134505) and to its arXiv preprint establishes a clear provenance chain that is increasingly expected of high-quality computational materials science outputs.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The most concrete evidence of uptake is a direct data citation from the companion journal article, confirmed through Crossref. While a single citation reflects the dataset's very recent publication, the citing work itself has already accumulated six citations of its own, suggesting that the broader research contribution is gaining traction within the superconductivity and computational physics communities. The reuse graph extends further: eight downstream scholarly connections are recorded in DataCite metadata, linking the dataset to foundational SIESTA publications, scientific software repositories, and community tools such as the AiiDA-SIESTA plugin \u2014 indicating that the work is positioned at the intersection of method development and open research infrastructure.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Online attention stands at ten recorded mentions, pointing to modest but real visibility beyond formal citation channels. This level of discourse is not unusual for a specialist computational dataset in its first year of availability, where community uptake typically travels through code repositories, workflow platforms, and targeted mailing lists rather than broad public channels. The green open-access status of the associated article further supports discoverability and downstream reuse without institutional barriers.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Taken together, the dataset reflects a responsible and well-structured open data practice: it is formally linked to its generating publication, contextualised within the SIESTA software ecosystem, and deposited on a domain-specific trusted repository. Its impact at this early stage is appropriately measured \u2014 a confirmed data citation, an active reuse graph, and a companion article accruing citations \u2014 while the foundational nature of the methodological contribution suggests that broader adoption within computational superconductivity research remains plausible as the community engages with the new capabilities the SIESTA implementation offers.</p>",
